Example

Solve the inequality \(|5x-2|<4\) and depict the solution graphically.

Solution

We treat each part of the inequality separately: \[\begin{aligned} -4 &< 5x-2 \\ -2 &< 5x \qquad \hbox{ by adding 2 to both sides} \\ -{2\over 5} &< x \qquad \hbox{ by dividing both sides by 5}\end{aligned}\] So \(x>-{2\over5}\). Now consider the second part: \(5x-2<4\). \[\begin{aligned} 5x-2 &< 4 \\ 5x &< 6 \qquad \hbox{ by adding 2 to both sides}\\ x &< {6\over 5} \qquad \hbox{ by dividing both sides by 5}\end{aligned}\] Putting both parts of the solution together we see that the inequality is satisfied when
\(\displaystyle{-{2\over 5}<x<{6\over 5}}\). This range of values is shown in the figure below.
